In [[cryptanalysis]], a '''kiss''' is a pair of identical messages sent using different ciphers, one of which has been broken. The term was used at [[Bletchley Park]] during [[World War II]]. A deciphered message in the breakable system provided a "[[crib (cryptanalysis)|crib]]" (piece of known plaintext) which could then be used to read the unbroken messages. One example was where messages read in a German [[meteorology|meteorological]] cipher could be used to provide cribs for reading the difficult 4-wheel Naval [[Enigma Machine|Enigma]] cipher.
:''cribs from re-encipherments .... were known as 'kisses' in Bletchley Park parlance because the relevant signals were marked with 'xx' ''<ref>Smith & Erskine (2001) p 69</ref>
